## Building an Avatar Group in Angular

**Mental model:** Show the first N avatars overlapping, then a "+X" bubble for the rest. Pure slicing via getters: `visible = users.slice(0, max)`, `overflow = users.length - max`. Overlap is negative margin plus a ring. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Inputs + derived getters
```typescript
@Input() users: User[] = [];
@Input() max = 4;
get visible(): User[] { return this.users.slice(0, this.max); }
get overflow(): number { return Math.max(0, this.users.length - this.max); }
```

### Step 2 — Overlap with negative margin
Bind `margin-left` off the loop index.

```html
<div *ngFor="let u of visible; let i = index" [style.margin-left]="i === 0 ? '0' : '-12px'">
  {{ initials(u.name) }}
</div>
```

### Step 3 — Initials + deterministic colour
```typescript
initials(name: string): string {
  return name.split(' ').map((w) => w[0]).slice(0, 2).join('').toUpperCase();
}
```

### Step 4 — The +X bubble
```html
<div *ngIf="overflow > 0" class="avatar more">+{{ overflow }}</div>
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Fewer than max | No "+X" bubble. |
| Broken image | Fall back to initials. |
| Recompute | Getters re-slice on each change detection. |

**Interview tip:** Deriving `visible`/`overflow` with getters keeps the component a pure function of its inputs — and binding `margin-left` off the loop index is the clean way to express the overlap without per-item state.

